04132nam a22005655i 9780226438351DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016034777  a9780226438351  a(DE-B1597)523391  a(OCoLC)973223165  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHM743.T95bH644 2017 7aPHI0000002bisacsh  aER 9652rvk0(DE-625)rvk/27783:1 aHodgkin, Adam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFollowing Searle on Twitter :bHow Words Create Digital Institutions /cAdam Hodgkin. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b1 halftone, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Philosophical Tweets -- t2. What Twitter Really Is -- t3. “Following” Makes Twitter’s Social Structure -- t4. “Almost Everything You See Today in Twitter Was Invented by Our Users” -- t5. Referential Complications -- t6. Twitter’s Content and Twitter’s Context -- t7. Twitter’s Constitution and Twitter’s Shape -- t8. Digital Institutions -- t9. Digital Language -- t10. A Natural History of Digital Institutions -- t11. Since We Make These Digital Institutions . . . -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTwitter allows us to build communities, track celebrities, raise our social profile, and promote a personal brand. Adam Hodgkin thinks Twitter is much more than a mere social media tool—it is a terrain ripe for a conceptual and theoretical analysis of our use of digital language. In Following Searle on Twitter, Hodgkin takes John Searle’s theory of speech acts as Status Function Declarations (SFDs)—speech acts that fulfill their meaning by saying the right words in the right context—as a probe for understanding Twitter’s institutional structure and the still-developing toolset that it provides for its members. He argues that Twitter is an institution built, constituted, and evolving through the use of SFDs. Searle’s speech act theories provide a framework for illuminating how Twitter membership arises, how users of Twitter relate to each other by following, and how increasingly complex content is conveyed with tweets. Using this framework, Hodgkin places language, action, intention, and responsibility at the core of the digital culture and the digital institutions that we are constructing. Combining theoretical perspective with a down-to-earth exposition of present-day digital institutions, Following Searle on Twitter explores how all of our interactions with these emerging institutions are deeply rooted in language, and are the true foundation of social media and contemporary institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aSocial networks. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aTwitter.  acollective intentionality.  acontent.  adigital institution.  afollowing.  alanguage.  astatus function declaration.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226438351423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226438351/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles